) + <i>mere</i> ‘lake’."],"variants":[{"name":"Bowmer","meanings":["English (Derbyshire): variant of   Bulmer  .","Americanized form of German   Baumer  ."]},{"name":"Bolmer","meanings":["English: variant of   Bulmer  .","Dutch: probably from the ancient Germanic personal name <i>Baldemar</i>, composed of the elements <i>bald</i> ‘bold’ + <i>mar</i> ‘famous’."]}]},{"name":"Alan","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Of Celtic origin and uncertain derivation (possibly a diminutive of a word meaning ‘rock’). It was introduced into England by  Breton  followers of  William the Conqueror , most notably  Alan , Earl of Brittany, who was rewarded for his services with vast estates in the newly conquered kingdom. In Britain the variants  <b>Allan</b>  and  <b>Allen</b>  are considerably less frequent, and generally represent transferred uses of surname forms, whereas in America all three forms of the name are approximately equally common.  See also  Alun ."],"variants":[]}],"lifeSummary":"Alan de Bulmer was born about 1040, in Normandy, France as the son of Henry de Bulmer. He married Joan de Powther. They were the parents of at least 1 son. He died about 1106, at the age of 68."},"et":{"Abt 1040–about 1106":"umbes 1040–umbes 1106","1040–1106":"1040–1106","1055–Female":"1055–Surnud","1070–1129":"1070–1129","1020–1066":"1020–1066","1129":"1129","1106":"1106","Abt 1040":"umbes 1040","about 1070":"umbes 1070","about 1106":"umbes 1106","1066":"1066","1055":"1055","1020":"1020","after 1066":"pärast 1066","1040":"1040","1070":"1070","Yorkshire, England":"Yorkshire, England","Normandy, France":"Normandie, Prantsusmaa"},"fi":{"Abt 1040–about 1106":"noin 1040–noin 1106","1040–1106":"1040–1106","1055–Female":"1055–Kuollut","1070–1129":"1070–1129","1020–1066":"1020–1066","1129":"1129","1106":"1106","Abt 1040":"noin 1040","about 1070":"noin 1070","about 1106":"noin 1106","1066":"1066","1055":"1055","10